## Step 1 — The core idea behind Docker volume mapping
    
        Containers are ephemeral.
            If a container is deleted, everything inside it is lost.
            So Docker gives us two ways to persist data:
                1️⃣ Bind Mounts

                    Map a host folder → container folder
                    You control the path.


                2️⃣ Named Volumes
                
                    Map a named volume → container folder
                    Docker manages the path and the he storage under /var/lib/docker/volumes.
            
            Both achieve persistence, but they behave differently.

## Quick Check: If a container writes logs to /var/log/app, and you delete the container, what happens to those logs without any volume mapping?

    - The logs will be lost because the container is ephemeral and all data inside it will be deleted when the container is removed.

## Step 2 — Bind Mounts (host folder --> Container folder)
      
      Definition (simple):
            A bind mount maps a real folder on your host to a folder inside the container.
        
        Example:
            docker run -v /home/atul/app:/usr/share/nginx/html nginx
            
            Meaning:
                • Left side = host path
                • Right side = container path
            
            So if you edit files in /home/atul/app, they instantly appear inside the container.

        Why bind mounts are useful?
            • Live code editing (Node.js, Python, React, etc.)
            • Sharing config files
            • Debugging
            • Local development

## Quick Check: If you run, 
        docker run -v /home/atul/data:/data busybox

            And you create a file inside the container: 

        echo "hello" > /data/msg.txt

            Where will this file actually be stored on your host machine? 

        - The file will be stored in the /home/atul/data directory on the host machine, because the bind mount maps that host folder to the /data folder inside the container.

    A bind mount is literally this:
            There is no copying.
            There is no syncing.
            It is a direct live link.
        So:
        • If the container writes → it writes to the host
        • If the host edits → the container sees it instantly
        • If the host deletes → the container loses it instantly
        This is why bind mounts are perfect for development, but risky for production.

    Hands-on:
        mkdir -p /Users/atulm/bind-demo
        cd /Users/atulm/bind-demo
        echo "Hello from host" > message.txt
        docker run -it --name bind-test -v /Users/atulm/bind-demo:/app \alpine sh
        ls app/
        cat app/message.txt



## Named Volumes (Docker‑managed storage)

    Definition (simple):
        A named volume is a Docker-managed storage that you can attach to a container.
    
    Example:
        docker run -v mydata:/data busybox

        Here, "mydata" is the name of the volume. Docker will create it if it doesn't exist and manage its storage location.

    Why named volumes are useful?
        • Data persistence in production
        • Sharing data between containers
        • Backing up and restoring data
        • Decoupling storage from container lifecycle

    
    Hands-on:
        1) Create a named volume:
            docker volume create mydata
            docker volume ls # to list all volumes and see "mydata" created

        2) Run a container with the named volume:
            docker run -it --name testbox -v mydata:/appdata busybox

        3) Inside the container, create a file:
            echo "hello from named volume" > /appdata/msg.txt

        4) Exit the container and run another container with the same volume to see the file:
            docker run -it --name testbox2 -v mydata:/appdata busybox 
            cat /appdata/msg.txt

        You should see "hello from named volume" printed, demonstrating that the data persists across containers.
